Narrative:
On August [XXX], 2023 at 4:39 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Santa Monica, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traversing a roundabout at the intersection of [XXX] at [XXX] when it slowed to a stop for other vehicles approaching and in the roundabout. The front of the passenger car that was in the roundabout behind the Waymo AV made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 9:54 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a heavy truck on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling northbound on [XXX] when it approached a heavy truck and trailer that was stopped in the adjacent lane on the left side of the street. As the Waymo began to slowly pass the truck, the truck initiated a reversing turn maneuver into a loading bay on the left side of [XXX]. The Waymo AV then came to a stop, and as the Waymo AV was initiating its own reversing maneuver to clear the path for the truck, the right side of the trailer made contact with the front driver's side corner of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 5:49 PM PT the mirror of a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, CA was struck by a cyclist on [XXX]. Drive at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was stopped in traffic on eastbound [XXX] Drive at the intersection with [XXX], when a cyclist that had been traveling behind the Waymo AV passed the Waymo AV on the left. As the cyclist passed the Waymo AV, the cyclist made contact with the driver side mirror of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position). The Waymo AV sustained damage and the cyclist did not stop, leaving the scene without exchanging information.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 4:45 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV entered the slip lane which connects westbound [XXX] to northbound [XXX] and came to a stop to yield to cross-traffic on [XXX]. As the Waymo AV was stopped, the front of the passenger car which was traveling behind the Waymo AV made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position). The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 1:05 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving an SUV on [XXX] near [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling northbound on [XXX]. As the SUV was passing the Waymo AV to the left, it initiated a right lane change. The front of the SUV made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage, and the SUV left the scene without exchanging information.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023, Waymo received notice of an allegation that a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV")  contributed to a low-speed collision between a fire engine and an SUV on [XXX] at [XXX].
On August 16th, 2023 at 6:11 PM PT, a Waymo AV operating in San Francisco, California was stopped at a red light in the dedicated left turn lane on the left side of northeast-bound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX]. While the light was red, a fire engine approached the Waymo AV from behind and the Waymo AV moved forward as far as possible before entering the intersection at [XXX]. After the light turned green and as the Waymo AV was calculating a path into the intersection to clear the way, the fire engine maneuvered around the Waymo AV on the right side. During this maneuver, the right side of the fire engine appears to have made contact with the front left corner of an SUV that was stopped in the through lane to the right of the Waymo AV. The fire engine then proceeded through the intersection, and shortly afterwards, another fire engine and a fire department SUV passed on the left side the Waymo AV of the stopped Waymo AV. The Waymo AV then proceeded through the intersection.
At the time of the collision, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The SUV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 9:01 PM a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling southwestbound on [XXX] in the second lane from the left as it was approaching [XXX]. As the Waymo AV was proceeding straight through the intersection, the passenger car in the right adjacent lane made a left turn from a straight-only lane onto southeastbound [XXX]. The rear of the passenger car made contact with the front of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. Both the Waymo AV and the passenger car sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 7:38 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a recycling bin on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was pulling over to the right side of the road, when the test driver transitioned to manual mode and made contact with a recycling bin on the right side of the street. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 7:23 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Phoenix, Arizona was in a collision involving an SUV on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling north on [XXX] through the intersection with [XXX]. An SUV traveling West on [XXX] entered the intersection without stopping at the two-way stop sign on [XXX]. The Waymo AV slowed to a stop in the intersection and the front left corner of the SUV made contact with the front right corner of the Waymo AV. 
At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 3:36 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Mesa, Arizona was in a collision involving a pickup truck on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was stationary adjacent to the curb on the West side of [XXX]. A pickup truck approached the Waymo from behind and slowed to a stop immediately behind the Waymo. The pickup truck then moved slowly forward until the front of the pickup truck was touching the rear of the Waymo AV. The pickup truck then slowly pushed into the rear of the Waymo AV for a few seconds before reversing, maneuvering around the Waymo AV, and leaving the scene. 
At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 10:09 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving an SUV on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was stopped at a red light on eastbound [XXX] at [XXX]. Shortly after the traffic light turned green and the Waymo AV began to proceed forward, the Waymo AV slowed to a stop. The SUV that was traveling closely behind the Waymo AV made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage, and the trailing SUV left the scene without exchanging information. A passenger in the Waymo AV reported injuries. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 7:12 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo") operating in Phoenix, Arizona was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was stationary adjacent to the curb on the south side of [XXX]. A passenger car which had been parked in front of the Waymo AV began reversing and the rear of the passenger car made contact with the front of the Waymo AV. The passenger car then left the scene. At the time of the impact, the Waymo's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On September 14, 2023, GM Cruise Holdings LLC ("Cruise") filed an Incident Report (the "Report") under the Second Amended Standing General Order 2021-01, dated April 5, 2023 (the "Order") General Motors LLC (GM) manufactured the Cruise-operated motor vehicle involved in the incident summarized in the Incident Report. Because GM is also a Reporting Entity under the Order, GM is submitting a duplicate of the redacted public copy of the Report. GM has selected "Unknown" in the "ADS version" and "ODD time" fields solely to avoid a second submission of nonpublic Cruise CBI GM is in possession of Cruise's responses to these fields, and incorporates Cruise's responses into this submission by reference. GM's submission is based on facts supplied to GM by Cruise. GM has not investigated the alleged incident and currently believes, based on a reasonable inquiry, that it has no independent knowledge of the facts in the Report. (Reference file: 30412-6282-1)

A Cruise autonomous vehicle ("AV"), operating in driverless autonomous mode, was at a complete stop in response to a four-way stop on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX]. As the AV was proceeding after clearing the intersection, a white SUV traveling westbound on [XXX] failed to stop, entered the intersection, and made contact with the AV, damaging the front bumper fascia and driver side front wheel molding of the AV. The driver of white SUV left the scene without exchanging information. There were no reported injuries. [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]

A Cruise autonomous vehicle ("AV"), operating in driverless autonomous mode, was traveling southbound on [XXX] in the left lane between [XXX] and [XXX]. After the AV passed the intersection with [XXX], the AV braked and, shortly thereafter, a black Dodge Ram traveling behind the AV rear-ended the AV, damaging the rear bumper fascia, rear window panel and driver side rear headlamp assembly of the AV. The parties exchanged information and there were no reported injuries. [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]

A Cruise autonomous vehicle ("AV"), operating in driverless autonomous mode, was at a complete stop in response to a red light on eastbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX]. At the same time, a large truck pulling a trailer traveling northbound on [XXX] was making an illegal U-turn inside the intersection. As the AV proceeded straight after the light turned green, the end of the large truck's trailer had not fully cleared the AV's lane of travel and made contact with the AV, damaging the AV's front bumper fascia, front camera, front grille assembly and front passenger side headlamp. The driver of the large truck left the scene without exchanging information. There were no reported injuries. [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]

A Cruise autonomous vehicle ("AV"), operating in driverless autonomous mode, was traveling eastbound on [XXX] between [XXX] and [XXX]. As the AV was coming to a stop for a stop sign at the intersection with [XXX], a silver Toyota Prius approaching from the rear failed to stop behind the AV and made contact with the AV's rear bumper, damaging the AV's rear sensor. The driver of the Toyota Prius left the scene without exchanging information. There were no reported injuries. [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]

A Cruise autonomous vehicle ("AV"), operating in driverless autonomous mode, was traveling southbound on [XXX] between [XXX] and [XXX]. At the same time, a Ford pickup truck was traveling northbound on [XXX] partially in the AV's lane of travel. The AV stopped due to limited space to proceed forward due to the encroaching Ford pickup truck, and, shortly thereafter, the Ford pickup truck made contact with the AV, damaging the AV's rear driver side bumper fascia, rear driver side quarter panel and rear driver side wheel molding. The driver of the Ford pickup truck left the scene without exchanging information. There were no reported injuries. [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]

A Cruise autonomous vehicle (AV"), operating in driverless autonomous mode, was traveling eastbound on [XXX] in the leftmost lane between [XXX] and [XXX]. A Ghost autonomous vehicle was hit by crash debris while traveling on [XXX].  The Ghost vehicle neither hit nor was hit by another vehicle.  The Ghost car was traveling in AV mode with two safety drivers.  Traffic slowed quickly, apparently due to a crash ahead of the Ghost car.  Consistent with their training, the Ghost driver took control of the car by manually braking and disengaging the autonomous system.  The car was traveling 55.3 mph when the driver began to brake.  The Ghost car stopped without impacting the preceding car.  A Mercedes car immediately following the Ghost car also came to a stop without impacting the Ghost car.  Ghost's understanding based on communications at the scene is that a Grand Cherokee traveling behind the Mercedes tried to swerve to avoid impacting the Mercedes but clipped the Mercedes and rolled over.  To Ghost's knowledge, nobody in the Grand Cherokee was injured.  The Ghost drivers heard a noise and then found that the rear bumper of the Ghost car had been damaged, which Ghost believes resulted from crash debris. The Ghost drivers drove the Ghost car back to the garage in conventional mode.

Narrative:
On June [XXX], 2023, at 9:42 PM PDT, a Motional Hyundai Ioniq 5 was operating in autonomous mode with a safety driver at the wheel and a safety operator in the front passenger seat.
 
The Motional vehicle was northbound on [XXX], in the left-most of two left turn lanes, turning onto [XXX] at 10 MPH. The Motional vehicle then braked for an approaching taxi in the adjacent turn lane that was perceived to be crossing into the lane of the Motional vehicle and was rear-ended by a silver Toyota traveling behind it.

On July [XXX], 2023 at 6:13 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in Chandler, Arizona was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling northbound on [XXX] and just passed [XXX] when an oncoming passenger car crossed into the Waymo AVs lane, toward the Waymo AV. The Waymo AV then stopped as the passenger vehicle continued to approach. The passenger vehicle then made contact with the front of the Waymo AV, and then made contact with the side of the Waymo AV as it left the scene. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage.

Federal Regulatory Exemption?: Part 591 Exemption granted by permission letter from NHTSA
Narrative:
On June 23, 2023, Motional informed HMNA's NASO of a crash incident occurring on June [XXX], 2023, at 9:42 PM PDT, involving a Hyundai IONIQ 5 test vehicle operating in proprietary ADS autonomous mode with a safety driver at the wheel and a safety operator in the front passenger seat.  According to Motional, the test vehicle was travelling northbound in the left-most of two left turn lanes on a local road at approximately 10 mph.  The test vehicle then braked for an approaching taxi in the adjacent lane that appeared to be crossing into the Motional test vehicle's lane and was rear-ended by a silver Toyota from behind.  The Toyota vehicle fled the scene of the accident.
Hyundai understands that the equipment and software used during the test is proprietary to Motional and not used as OEM equipment in any Hyundai/Genesis vehicle produced for sale to the general public.  Hyundai currently does not offer an ADS feature on any vehicle offered for sale in the U.S. market.

On [XXX], 2023, while in supervised ("Drivered") autonomous mode with Pony.ai's ADS engaged, a Pony.ai AV was rear-ended twice, in quick succession, by a passenger vehicle. The incident occurred at the intersection of [XXX] and [XXX] in Fremont, CA. At the time of the incident, the Pony.ai AV was stopped at a red light on [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX], heading west-southwest. The incident occurred when a passenger vehicle directly behind the Pony.ai AV proceeded to rear-end the Pony.ai AV two times in quick succession. Following the incident, the Pony.ai safety operator disengaged the AV from autonomous mode. Concerned for his safety, the Pony.ai operator immediately drove the vehicle back to the Pony.ai Fremont office (a distance of approximately 1 mile). The passenger vehicle which had rear-ended the Pony.ai AV followed it back to Pony.ai's Fremont office. After a brief interaction during which the driver of the striking vehicle threatened Pony.ai employees, the driver of that vehicle drove away. The Fremont police were called by Pony.ai staff, and they responded and took a report about the incident. There were no injuries reported. The Fremont Police Department report number is [XXX].

After submitting the previous 1-Day report on [XXX], 2023 [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION], Waymo received notice that the test driver was not transported from the scene to the hospital for medical treatment, but did seek medical treatment at a hospital at a later time. As such, this event could have qualified for a 5-Day report. The narrative below has been updated to reflect this information. This updated report also now lists the Highest Injury Severity Alleged as moderate, and Transdev Alternative Services as an entity that may be aware of this incident.
On [XXX], 2023 at 1:17 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in Phoenix, AZ was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] in the southbound direction near the [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling in the rightmost lane (out of 5 lanes) in the southbound direction of [XXX],  and the left 3 lanes were closed due to a work zone. The vehicle traveling ahead in the same lane as the ADV made an abrupt lane change to the left, revealing a stack of slow-moving vehicles in the Waymo AVs lane. The test driver of the Waymo AV took manual control of the vehicle and started to decelerate and steer toward the right shoulder in response to slow traffic ahead. A passenger vehicle approached the Waymo AV from behind and made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver (in the drivers seating position) was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. The Waymo AV and the other vehicle sustained damage. The test driver reported an injury, for which they later sought medical treatment. 
Waymo reported this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On Monday May [XXX] at 11:41am a Weride autonomous vehicle (Vehicle 1) was in Autonomous Mode stopped at the intersection of [XXX] towards [XXX] appropriately yielding to a illegally U turning skateboard on [XXX] North to South direction in front of the AV (Vehicle 1). While yielding, a bicyclist was coming from behind our AV (Vehicle 1) head was turned left possibly looking for cross traffic. When the cyclist turned his head forward, it was too late to react in time to our stopped vehicle(Vehicle 1) with the given distance and speed they were traveling at in which the cyclist collided with our vehicle (Vehicle 1). Our Weride safety officer immediately disengaged and hand signaled to the bicyclist to pull over to the closest safe place to park as to not obstruct traffic. As our safety officer parked and got out of the car to check on the bicyclist, the bicyclist was already on in motion on his bicycle and "fist bumped" our safety officer while passing by him and leaving the scene without exchanging any information.

On Friday April [XXX] at 16:16 local time, the May shuttle was driving Westbound on [XXX] in Ann Arbor, MI in autonomous mode and was followed by another vehicle. The following vehicle was traveling approximately twice as fast as the May shuttle and catching up to the May shuttle from behind. The May shuttle began to slow for traffic ahead, which was stopping for a red light, but the following vehicle did not decelerate. While slowing, the May shuttle identified a bollard on the side of the road as a likely pedestrian and added a safety buffer which intersected with the predicted trajectory of the shuttle. This caused the shuttle to increase deceleration to avoid the projected collision with the buffer. The following vehicle started braking late and impacted the May shuttle from behind with a relative velocity of 6.2 m/s. Re-simulation of this event with a future software version shows that the May shuttle would have decelerated less abruptly.

Operating Entity: Mercedes-Benz Research and Development North America
Narrative: The subject Mercedes-Benz vehicle was driving in stop and go traffic on the [XXX] in Gardena, California with the L3 ADS activated. The test route selected by the driver in the vehicle's navigation system indicated an upcoming exit, so the driver began to prepare for a lane change towards the highway exit by deactivating the L3 ADS and activating the turn signal. Once the vehicle was in conventional driving mode, the driver looked for a gap in the adjacent lane to merge towards the exit lane, applied the brakes, and slowed the vehicle down. The SUV following the Mercedes-Benz vehicle did not respond in time to the vehicle's braking and contacted the rear of the Mercedes-Benz approximately 10 seconds after the L3 ADS was deactivated.  The Mercedes-Benz vehicle experienced minor damage to the rear bumper. No injuries were reported, no airbags deployed in either vehicle, and both vehicles were driven from the scene of the incident.

Operating Entity: Mercedes-Benz Research and Development North America
Narrative: Mercedes-Benz has conducted a review of the incident and the following is based on that review. The subject Mercedes-Benz Drive Pilot test vehicle was traveling between 15-20 mph in the #2 northbound lane on the [XXX] in California in stop and go traffic with the L3 ADS activated by the driver. The vehicle's ADS determined that a truck traveling in the adjacent lane had a trajectory towards the Drive Pilot's lane, and so the Mercedes-Benz test vehicle autonomously applied the brakes to avoid a collision. After applying the brakes and bringing itself to a standstill, the Mercedes-Benz was then struck in the rear bumper by a trailing semi-truck that did not stop in time. No injuries were reported, no airbags deployed in either vehicle, and both vehicles were able to be driven from the scene of the incident. The Mercedes-Benz vehicle experienced minor damage to the rear bumper, and no damage was observed on the semi-truck at the scene. The CA Traffic Collision Report for the subject incident noted a violation of California Vehicle Code 22350 (unsafe speed for traffic conditions) by the semi-truck in the #2 lane that struck the rear bumper of the Mercedes-Benz.

On January [XXX], 2023, RRAI received a support request through their Customer Support Portal from Beep, Inc., the owner of the vehicle, regarding their Olli 2.0 vehicle bumping into the curb in Peachtree Corners, GA. At 11:01 am, while running the normal route, the Olli contacted the adjacent curb on the front right side, causing tie rod and cosmetic damage. No one was injured and the only damage was to the vehicle itself. The customer contacted RRAI through the client support portal shortly after the incident. No injuries occurred, there were no passengers besides the safety operator, no other vehicles were involved, and no emergency systems were engaged.
Olli 2.0 (S/N 2-18) is an 8-passenger shuttle that is no longer manufactured. The vehicle manufacturer, Local Motors, dissolved in 2022. Local Motors contracted RRAI to install autonomy kits for several Olli shuttles during the period of 2018 - 2020. RRAI provided some support for initial site deployment and ensured customer safety operators were trained on the autonomy system. Since the Local Motors dissolution in 2022, almost all Olli vehicles have been decommissioned.
To date, we have concluded the following:
1. There were no updates or alterations made by RRAI in the months prior to Jan [XXX]. In previous operations, including the immediately preceding operations on January 20th, 2023, Olli 2-18 ran the route as normal with no anomalies. There were no software updates or other system changes before it was run again on January [XXX], 2023, the date of curb contact.
2. The root cause of the curb contact was a communication error with the HD Map registration module. HD Map registration utilizes real-time lidar and positioning data and compares that to a-priori HD maps stored within the autonomy system. A communication problem occurred between the computer running the map registration software and the computer running the navigation algorithms. The cause for the communication problem has been identified and a fix has been implemented to prevent the issue from happening again (see below).
3. Steering was out of calibration. It was noted through data collection that the steering was out of calibration at time of incident. The autonomy system was attempting to correct this issue, but the vehicular steering system could not achieve the required turn radius. This is a vehicular maintenance concern managed by the customer.
It was determined that the HD map registration issue had not been observed during autonomous operations in the previous four years. The solution to prevent further occurrences includes:
1. Implementing a self-diagnostic routine upon system boot, which ensures the communication connection is established. If the connection is not established, this diagnostic will prevent the vehicle from driving autonomously. 
2. Updating the error checks to ensure that during run time, the vehicle will come to a controlled stop in event of a communication problem.  
3. Working with the customer to recalibrate the steering, and assisting in reviewing customer's vehicle maintenance checks for steering calibration if necessary.
4. Continuing to review data to determine other concerns or improvements.

Lucid has received telematics and notification from a Lucid Service Center that a 2022 Lucid Air was traveling southbound on [XXX] in Los Alamitos, California on 1/[XXX]/2023 with Level 2 ADAS engaged when it struck another vehicle which from the front camera shows a collision with a semi-truck bumper, just before sunrise at 6:53 am PST. On January [XXX], 2023 at 1:38 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in Phoenix, Arizona was in a collision with a minibike whose rider was no longer on it on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling in the leftmost lane on eastbound [XXX], with a group of smaller motorcycles, more commonly known as minibikes, traveling in the right adjacent lane next to and ahead of the Waymo AV. A minibike rider in the group lost control and fell off the minibike a short distance ahead of the Waymo AV in the adjacent lane and the minibike, without a rider, tumbled into the Waymo AV's lane. The Waymo AV applied maximum brake force but made contact with the riderless minibike just before coming to a stop. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage. The minibike was damaged but it is not possible to determine whether all or some of that damage occurred when the minibike fell to the road before the collision. Because we checked on the minibike riders well-being shortly after the crash, Waymo is aware that the individual sustained minor injuries when they fell from the minibike but the subsequent collision with the riderless minibike did not cause those injuries.
Although we do not believe this event falls under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01, we consulted NHTSA and submitted this report at the agencys request on the day of the consultation. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

Information indicates a 2023 Lucid Air, traveling Southeast bound on [XXX] between Santa Barbara, CA, and Ventura, CA, was involved in a crash at 5:04 pm Pacific Time on December [XXX], 2022. Due to road construction the vehicle followed the lane markings, which switch southbound traffic to a designated lane on the northbound side of the road. Online weather information for the area indicates sunset was at approximately 5pm and it was cloudy and rainy. Telematics indicate the vehicle was traveling at 70 mph a few seconds prior to the crash and the pre-crash speed was 43 mph. The customer called Lucid Customer Care and reported that he hit a pothole and the vehicle veered into the concrete barrier dividing the southbound traffic from the northbound traffic, resulting in the left driver side curtain air bag being deployed on impact. The vehicle was towed following the crash.  The customer reported that no one was injured. Telematics indicate Lucid's Highway Assist feature (SAE Level 2) was active until approximately 3 seconds prior to the accident, when HWA deactivated due to inability to detect the lane markings, most likely due to environmental conditions. The driver distraction warning feature had been turned off. At the time of HWA deactivation, and through the crash time, telematics indicates the customer had hands on the steering wheel and was actively steering. Vehicle acceleration data approximately 1 second prior to the crash is consistent with the driver's report of hitting a pothole. Vehicle acceleration data and the side curtain airbag deployment are consistent with the driver's report of hitting the concrete barrier separating southbound from northbound traffic.

On December [XXX], 2022, a Navya ARMA shuttle operated by Beep (VIN 1N9A1SACXJS[XXX]) was involved in a non-injury collision while operating in manual mode on [XXX] in Port Saint Lucie, FL.  While driving along [XXX] under autonomous control, the shuttle encountered a parked vehicle partially blocking its path, requiring disengagement of the autonomous drive system.  The safety driver attempted to manually drive the shuttle around the parked vehicle to reengage the autonomous drive system.  While manually steering the shuttle around the parked vehicle blocking its path, the shuttle failed to respond to manual control input and steered to the left, impacting a parked vehicle at a low rate of speed on the opposite side of [XXX].  The six passengers onboard alighted the shuttle, an accident report was filed with the local police, and the shuttle was removed from the scene.  Initial reports from the onboard safety driver indicated that while steering around the vehicle blocking the shuttle's path, the shuttle became unresponsive to control input.  The safety driver released the operator present button on the vehicle controller, which serves as dead man switch however, the vehicle failed to stop.  After the incident, further investigation by Navya confirmed that the root cause of the incident was a failure of the Xbox 360 controller used to manually control the vehicle.  Contact with the parked vehicle occurred between the time of failure and the vehicle drive system recognizing that the controller had failed an elapsed time of 4.05 seconds. In response to the incident, Beep suspended operation of all Navya ARMA vehicles pending identification and implementation of appropriate solutions to mitigate the risk of this failure leading to future incidents.
Subsequent investigation by Beep and Navya determined that the vehicle control software, NavyaDrive, is limited in its ability to monitor the validity of control signal input received from the Xbox 360 controller.  As the safety driver began to manually steer the vehicle, the controller failed, sending constant turning input to the vehicle drive system leading to the collision.  Though Navya developed software mitigations due to prior issues encountered with the controller, those mitigations were ineffective with respect to the failure leading to the incident on December [XXX].  Further, due to the short time between the controller failing and the collision (2.34sec), the safety driver was unable to identify the controller failure and trigger the emergency stop before the collision occurred.
In response to the incident, Navya is integrating a revised manual control system on the ARMA shuttle platform.  The revised manual control system utilizes industrial-grade components for improved electromechanical reliability and allows for active monitoring of the control system health, eliminating the root cause of the failure that led to the incident on December [XXX].  Software upgrades of all Navya ARMA vehicles will further reintroduce automated braking function while the ARMA vehicle is under manual control.  Beep is working with Navya to retrofit its fleet of ARMA vehicles with the revised manual control system as well as retrain and recertify its safety driver staff on the updated NavyaDrive software.
Discussion of the root cause analysis and solution design for the revised manual control system will be provided to NHTSA as a supplement to this report.

The initial submission was by email and electronic form to SGO Mailbox on 10/18/2022 at 10:09PM.  This is a resubmission of data using the SGO portal with Volvo Cars USA, LLC account on behalf of Polestar Automotive USA. Volvo Cars USA, LLC is submitting this report on behalf of Polestar Automotive USA and Polestar Performance AB.  The vehicle was a company vehicle (owned by Polestar Automotive USA) driven by a company employee, with no known modifications to the factory hardware condition or software updates or changes not released to the public. Subject vehicle was traveling around a curve on the freeway interchange at approximately 55mph, recommended speed in that portion of exchange was 50mph.  Driver looked down and took attention off the road.  The vehicle continued slightly straight, running up and grazing off the concrete barrier, before coming back into the lane.  The vehicle's rear suspension, rear and front wheel/tire were damaged. Vehicle was towed from the scene. We have recovered data from the vehicle and are currently reviewing what information was stored for the incident and will update this report.
10 Day update: After review of the EDR data the technical team was able to determine the following: Pilot Assist was disengaged due to the lateral acceleration exceeded the system limit and the available steering torque system input exceeding the limit.  The vehicle could not steer enough to follow the lane. Several warnings were issued: visually in the DIM (Drivers Information Module, display), haptically in the steering wheel, before Pilot Assist was disengaged. The driver is always responsible for ensuring that the vehicle is driven in a safe manner. The driver failed to take control of the vehicle when the vehicles Pilot Assist gave the warnings.

On Aug [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION], 2022 at [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] CST a Kodiak Autonomous Vehicle ("Kodiak AV") Class 8 semi-truck driving southbound on [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] in [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] Texas was rear-ended by a pickup truck. The Kodiak AV had been braking for over 11 seconds in lane to safely accommodate two pedestrians and their vehicles near the fog line on the shoulder when a pickup truck rear-ended the Kodiak AV. 
The Kodiak AV was operating with a safety driver (in the driver's seating position), who transitioned the vehicle from autonomous to manual mode immediately prior to impact. At the time of impact, the Kodiak AV was in manual mode.
No injuries occurred in the incident. The Kodiak AV's rear lightbar sustained minor damage, as did the pickup truck's front bumper and hood.  Both vehicles were able to drive away from the scene. 
Kodiak is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of the Standing General Order 2021-01 because the Kodiak AV was slowing down for vulnerable road users when it was rear-ended. Kodiak may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On June [XXX], 2022 at approximately 4:50 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California allegedly contributed to a collision between a passenger vehicle and a pickup truck on [XXX] at [XXX], according to a claim by the driver of the passenger vehicle.
The Waymo AV was in autonomous mode and preparing to enter southbound [XXX] as a passenger vehicle on [XXX] approached from behind.  A pickup truck was traveling next to the passenger vehicle in the adjacent left lane.  As the passenger vehicle approached the Waymo AV from behind, the passenger vehicle entered the adjacent left lane that was occupied by the pickup truck and maneuvered around the Waymo AV.  The pickup truck proceeded without stopping, and the passenger vehicle's driver shortly after signaled to the Waymo AV test driver to pull over.  The Waymo AV test driver then transitioned to manual mode and pulled over.  Transdev has no data or knowledge of any contact between any of the three vehicles.  There was no contact or collision between the Waymo AV and any other vehicle.  However, the driver and passenger in the passenger vehicle have subsequently alleged injuries based on alleged contact between the pick-up truck and passenger vehicle, which contact their allegations attribute to the behavior of Waymo's AV in a bodily injury claim under Waymo's insurance policy.  Waymo received notice of this insurance claim on July [XXX].
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this event under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This report is a duplicate of 30270-3655-1.

Subject Vehicle is a Lucid-owned vehicle used by Lucid employees and contract drivers to test and validate ADAS features under development by Lucid. The Subject Vehicle included Lucid "Highway Assist" (HWA) which is Level 2 ADAS technology under development by Lucid in collaboration with its suppliers. The HWA function combines lane-keeping and Adaptive Cruise Control (ACC), but is not yet available on vehicles that Lucid sells to the public. As a Level 2 technology, HWA requires the attention of the driver at all times and is not expected to avoid all accidents.
 
On 7/[XXX]/2022 at approximately 3:58 am, a contract test driver was driving a Lucid Air northbound on [XXX] at approximately 70 MPH. The driver reported that he engaged HWA and subsequently "blacked out, passed out, or fainted." The driver's supervisor initially reported that the driver fell asleep. The driver reported that he has not sought medical attention following the incident. Telemetered data confirms engagement of HWA and indicates that the driver imparted sufficient torque on the steering wheel to override HWA. When HWA is overridden, it no longer provides lane-keeping and ACC remains active. Approximately 15 seconds later, the vehicle drifted out of its lane and impacted its left side against the roadside barrier on the left side of the road. The driver awoke after the impact and brought the vehicle to a stop on the side of the freeway. Lucid roadside assistance was contacted to tow the vehicle. No airbags deployed. There were no other vehicles or people involved in this accident and the driver was not harmed.

Subject vehicle was on a testing mission in Mountain View, CA. All of the data in this report and the following text is an excerpt from TuSimples original submission (30370-2949-1) and constitutes Navistars sole understanding of this event.
TuSimple's position is that this event does not meet the criteria for reporting under the SGO.
Specifically, the L4 ADS was not in operation at any point in the 30 seconds prior to making contact with the concrete barrier.
The event occurred as follows:
As the truck was being operated on the highway, within its mapped ODD, the driver and test engineer attempted to engage the ADS.
However, the ADS was not functional at that moment due to the computer unit not having been initialized, and should not have been
attempted to be activated. In short, this was a failed attempt to engage the system as a result of human error.
The system has now been modified to prevent the ADS from attempting to engage unless the health of the system is fully functional to
prevent human error from repeating this event.
When the erroneous attempt to engage occurred, the uninitialized vehicle control unit rotated the steering to the left, causing the truck to
veer left. The safety driver took control of the steering, and was able to steer accordingly, but not before the left front truck tire and left
front quarter panel came into contact with the concrete barrier to the left of the lanes of travel.
Ford is updating its May 2022 Monthly report (submitted on 5/15/2022).  [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]

The Beep shuttle attendant was traveling Southbound on [XXX] at approx 7-12 mph in ADS and headed towards the intersection of [XXX]. Beep vehicle stopped at red light at intersection. As the Beep vehicle was crossing the intersection in manual and slowing to a stop to return to ADS in a southbound direction, the trailing bus made light contact with its bicycle rack to the Beep shuttle rear end. The trailing vehicle is a bus owned and operated by the Pinellas Suncoast Transit Authority (PSTA). According to video, as reported by the shuttle attendant and the PSTA Road Supervisor, the bus was tailgating. 
 
Root Cause: Trailing vehicle following too closely and not observing Navya slowing to a stop.

The May vehicle was traveling on an unpainted (no center line) residential road with vehicles parked along the right side of the road. The May vehicle passed too close to a parked vehicle, causing the May vehicle's passenger-side mirror to contact the parked vehicle's driver-side mirror.
The May vehicle's ground mapping module had fallen significantly behind in its processing of lidar data. As a result, actual objects were being filtered out of the lidar data during object detection. This filtering caused the truck to oscillate between being detected, detecting only the cab, detecting the cab and mirror, and not being detected at all.
After assessing the issue, it has been determined that ground map latency alone will not cause safety issues. There is no risk to VRUs, or anything at ground level. The issue was with something in the air (mirror), above the ground.
A permanent fix to address the ground map latency issue is in process and will be implemented in the entire fleet within the next 30 days.
The second factor in the collision is that we were artificially constraining the vehicle to the right side of the road due to ambiguous and unpainted roadway. If we change that constraint to an advisory line (and allow the vehicle to cross the line to the left), we would have been far enough to the left to avoid collision (simulation success).
Solution Implementation: AVO training for extra caution related to protruding items like mirrors (short term), software changes coming in the next update and hotfix (within 30 days), and further improvement in the following update (within 60 days).
Until the tested software changes are implemented, we have advised the AVOs to take extra caution in these scenarios and to continue to disengage autonomy when desired. As always, we sacrifice autonomy for safety, as needed.

TuSimple's position is that this event does not meet the criteria for reporting under the SGO.
Specifically, the L4 ADS was not in operation at any point in the 30 seconds prior to making contact with the concrete barrier.  
 
The event occurred as follows:
As the truck was being operated on the highway, within its mapped ODD, the driver and test engineer attempted to engage the ADS.  However, the ADS was not functional at that moment due to the computer unit not having been initialized, and should not have been attempted to be activated.  In short, this was a failed attempt to engage the system as a result of human error.  
 
The system has now been modified to prevent the ADS from attempting to engage unless the health of the system is fully functional to prevent human error from repeating this event.
 
When the erroneous attempt to engage occurred, the uninitialized vehicle control unit rotated the steering to the left, causing the truck to veer left.  The safety driver took control of the steering, and was able to steer accordingly, but not before the left front truck tire and left front quarter panel came into contact with the concrete barrier to the left of the lanes of travel.  
 
The contact resulted in a scuff to the left tire and damage to the radar unit extending from the left quarter panel.

The Waymo AV test driver then took manual control and stopped the Waymo AV. The SUV then stopped, reversed, and drove around the Waymo AV and made contact with the Waymo AV's driver side rear fender. At the time of the impact the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. The Waymo AV sustained minor damage and the SUV left the scene without exchanging information.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available. This report was submitted from the Pacific time zone on the required date.

On November [XXX], 2021 at 8:02 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ('Waymo AV') operating in San Francisco, CA was in a collision involving a passenger vehicle at [XXX], [XXX], and [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling southbound on [XXX], a narrow road with vehicles parked on both sides, and approaching the intersection with [XXX] and [XXX]. A passenger vehicle approaching from the right of the Waymo AV on eastbound [XXX] made a left turn in front of the Waymo AV to head northbound on [XXX]. The Waymo AV slowed to a near stop and nudged to its right in order to share the narrow road with the oncoming vehicle and then came to a stop at the stop sign as the oncoming vehicle completed its turn. At approximately 5 mph, the turning passenger vehicle made contact with Waymo AV's sensor hardware housing on the driver side rear corner fender of the stopped Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position). The Waymo AV sustained minor damage to the sensor hardware housing (which was the reason for towing the Waymo AV) and the passenger vehicle left the scene without exchanging information.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

Subject vehicle was on a testing mission in Sunnyvale, CA.  The vehicle was traveling South-bound on [XXX], an eight-lane divided road, operated by the vehicles Level 4 Automated Driving System and supervised by a safety driver in the drivers designated seating position, and with a safety operator in the front passenger seating position.  Subject vehicle moved to the right of the lane to turn right onto West-bound [XXX], a two-lane road, and made contact with a curb at approximately 13-miles per hour.  The safety driver was monitoring the behavior of a vehicle passing in the left lane for signs that it might enter subject vehicles path and did not see subject vehicle moving toward the curb in time to intervene and avoid contact.  During the incident, the safety driver disengaged the Automated Driving System, and then pulled the vehicle to the side of [XXX] and inspected the vehicle and curb for damage.  After the inspection, the safety driver drove the vehicle back to base with the Automated Driving System disengaged.  Subject vehicle did not sustain tire or wheel damage, but the contact resulted in misalignment.  No other agents were involved, no injuries were reported, and law enforcement was not called to the scene. Post-Crash Information: In addition to telematics and video, we also have photographs of the tires, curb, and alignment calibration information.

Other than the addition of the zip code in which the incident occurred, the content of this report is unchanged from the initial report submitted on September [XXX], 2021 [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]. On August [XXX], 2021 at 5:41 PM PDT, Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco was in a collision involving an unoccupied parked passenger vehicle at [XXX]. While performing a multipoint turn at the north end of [XXX] (a dead-end road), the Waymo AV was in reverse at approximately 2 MPH when it made contact with the front driver's side door of an unoccupied parked passenger vehicle. The Waymo AV was in autonomous mode until just before making contact, when the test driver transitioned the Waymo AV into manual mode. The contact caused minor scuffing and a small dent in the door handle of the parked vehicle's driver door and minor damage to the plastic sensor housing on the Waymo AV's rear passenger's side.Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because the Waymo AV was towed from the scene (though the Waymo AV was driveable). Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available. This report was submitted from the Pacific time zone on the required date.

Vehicle was moving forward and veered slightly to the left, making contact with the curb, resulting in a blown tire.
Curb strike occurred during testing. There was human error involved in defining the desired vehicle pose in the lane, which led to a curb strike. We have since resolved this by fixing the desired pose.

Vehicle made a right turn and struck the curb, causing a blown tire.
Vehicle elected a controller path mid corner, which caused the curb strike. We have assessed the localities where this could occur and are taking those turns in manual operation. We are currently testing a fix that will make our controller more aware of the curb to prevent future occurrences.

This report is an update to 30412-1138. A Cruise autonomous vehicle (Cruise AV), operating in autonomous mode, was traveling southbound on [XXX] between [XXX] and [XXX]. The Cruise AV was traveling 24.4 mph upon entering the intersection with [XXX] on a green light. As the Cruise AV continued through the intersection, a bicyclist traveling eastbound on [XXX] failed to stop for their red light and entered the intersection. The Cruise AV was disengaged from autonomous mode and the Cruise AV operator braked to a speed of 8.7 mph and, shortly thereafter, the bicyclist made contact with the Cruise AV, damaging the front of the Cruise AV and the bicycle. The cyclist verbally reported they were okay. However, the Cruise AV Operator noticed minor injuries to the cyclist. Police and Emergency Medical Services were called, but the cyclist left the scene before the police or EMS arrived. [REDACTED CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]

On September [XXX], 2021 at 1:54 PM PDT, a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ('Waymo AV') operating in Tempe, AZ was in a collision involving a pickup truck on [XXX] near [XXX]. While in autonomous mode, the Waymo AV began to enter the right lane of a protected double left turn lane ('Lane 2') from northbound [XXX] to westbound [XXX]. A pickup truck heading southbound on [XXX] had completely crossed the double-yellow lines of the northbound double left turn lanes and positioned itself in the left lane of the double turn lane ('Lane 1') facing the wrong direction against traffic and was preparing to make a left turn across Lane 2 and the other two northbound lanes into a shopping center parking lot on the east side of [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling in Lane 2 when the pickup truck began to initiate its left turn from Lane 1. The Waymo AV braked, and the trained human driver in the Waymo AV (in the driver's seating position), transitioned the vehicle from autonomous to manual mode. As the pickup truck made the left turn, the driver's side panels of the pickup truck made contact with the driver's side rear corner of the Waymo AV causing moderate damage to the Waymo AV. Damage to the pickup is currently unknown. At the time of contact, the Waymo AV was in manual mode.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because the Waymo AV was towed from the scene. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available. This report was submitted from the Pacific time zone on the required date.

- The subject vehicle of this report was procured by and up-fitted to ADS L4 by May Mobility with a May Mobility automated driving kit.
- The content of this report, including the summary of incident below, is the information as Toyota received from May Mobility on Aug [XXX], 2021.
Summary of incident (as Toyota received from May Mobility):
Leading up to the event, the autonomy system functioned as expected, following the route through the intersection, slowing appropriately for other road users and the red light. Vehicle autonomous behavior was performing as expected and did not require a takeover.
Description of event:
16:17:30 May vehicle, traveling East on [XXX], in full working order with no errors, autonomously navigates the [XXX] and [XXX] intersection.
16:17:35 May vehicle autonomously begins to slow to match the speed of a vehicle several car lengths ahead merging into our lane from the right.
16:17:37 By means of an accelerator pedal push the vehicle is moved into manual mode by the safety operator - from this point forward, the vehicle remains under control of the safety operator.
16:17:43 Manual acceleration command via the pedal increases.
16:17:44 Safety operator manually continues straight which, due to the slight change in angle of the road, brings the May vehicle into contact with the first vehicle to the right.
16:17:44 Safety operator manually applies brake.
16:17:45 With the manual brake command now at maximum the May vehicle makes contact with the second vehicle.
Vehicle indicators for manual or autonomy mode:
The visual indicator for autonomy was functioning properly and as expected in the time leading up to and during the event.
The audio communication device in the vehicle was functioning properly and was used to call for assistance and to report the incident.
The audio beep to indicate a state change was functioning properly.
The safety operator had some audio indication that he had exited autonomy and entered manual operation, and he had full visual indication on his dashboard.

At about 11:35 am our vehicle (car 1) was waiting behind a USPS truck to make an unprotected left turn, meanwhile one other vehicle (car 2) waited behind our vehicle.   Another non involved vehicle notices the queue of vehicles and passes on the right in the bike lane.  As the USPS truck begins to make the turn, car 1 begins to move forward at 7 MPH then slowed to 3 MPH when yielding to the vehicle passing in the bike lane. Car 2 directly behind us strikes our passenger rear bumper.  The safety driver then disengaged the vehicle (car 1) and moved into a nearby parking lot to exchange information.

On August [XXX], 2021 at 4:48 PM PDT, a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California was struck by a bicycle at [XXX] and [XXX]. The Waymo AV had stopped at a stop sign on [XXX] and, when the intersection was clear, began to proceed westbound through the intersection with [XXX]nue. At approximately the same time, a cyclist traveling northbound ran the stop sign on [XXX]nue, began to turn right onto [XXX] but immediately veered left to continue northbound across the crosswalk on [XXX], where it struck the rear driver?s side of the Waymo AV. The cyclist stayed upright and immediately rode away, continuing northbound on [XXX]nue. The bicycle caused minor scratches and marks on the rear driver?s side bumper of the Waymo AV. The Waymo AV was operating with a driver (in the driver?s seating position), who transitioned the vehicle from autonomous to manual mode approximately 1 second before the impact occurred. At the time of impact, the Waymo AV was in manual mode. Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user was involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.
